    <section>                                                          <!--12-->
      <title>Panama Papers: the Making Of</title>
      <subtitle>The History's Biggest Leak</subtitle>
      <abstract>
        The investigation was conducted by the Süddeutsche Zeitung and the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists, a global network of investigative journalists who collaborate on in-depth investigative stories.
      </abstract>
      <chapter>
        <paragraph>They have been involved:</paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>76 COUNTRIES</item>
            <item>109 MEDIA ORGANIZATIONS</item>
            <item>376 JOURNALISTS</item>
          </list>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>The leak has included:</paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>11.5 MILLION FILES</item>
            <item>2.6 TERABYTES</item>
          </list>
        </paragraph>
      </chapter>
      <chapter>
        <title>But the Full Package of Data Has Not Shared Yet</title>
        <paragraph>ICIJ director, Gerald Ryle, has said that the media organizations have no plans to release the full dataset, WikiLeaks-style, which he argues would expose the sensitive information of innocent private individuals.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>While a WikiLeaks survey on Twitter shows:</paragraph>
      </chapter>
      <graph unit="%" x="string" y="percentage">
